---
import { Picture } from "astro:assets"
import CaseStudy from "@/layouts/case-study.astro"
import CaseStudySnapshot from "@/components/CaseStudySnapshot.astro"
import { getProject } from "@/data/projects"
import letterheadImg from "@/assets/projects/ncga-stationery/letterhead-house.png"
import envelopeImg from "@/assets/projects/ncga-stationery/envelope-editor.png"

const project = getProject("ncga-stationery-templates")!

const pictureFormats: ("avif" | "webp")[] = ["avif", "webp"]
const pictureWidths = [640, 960, 1280]
const pictureSizes = "(min-width: 768px) 960px, 100vw"

const snapshotItems = [
  {
    label: "Problem",
    value:
      "Repeat NCGA stationery for all 170 members; per-legislator files led to inconsistent spacing, colors, and correction rounds.",
  },
  {
    label: "Primary users",
    value:
      "In-house print shop staff producing legislator letterhead and envelopes.",
  },
  {
    label: "Design move",
    value:
      "One locked internal template structure with a governed LegislatorRecord, so staff edit only what production allows.",
  },
  {
    label: "Result",
    value:
      "One governed template structure replaced per-legislator files, so personalized mailings to all 170 members run in a single press pass instead of two, with print-accurate preview, PDF export, and a cleaner handoff into mail merge.",
  },
]
---

<CaseStudy
  project={project}
  title="NCGA Stationery Template System"
  description="A constrained template engine for North Carolina General Assembly stationery: one locked structure, governed variable data, and print-accurate preview for all 170 legislators."
  seoTitle="NCGA Stationery Template System · Information Architecture"
  seoDescription="Designing a constrained template engine for NCGA legislator letterhead and envelopes: LOCKED vs DATA-DRIVEN fields, print-accurate preview, and fewer production mistakes."
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    The North Carolina General Assembly print shop produces repeat stationery
    for all 170 legislators, including business cards, letterhead,
    envelopes, and related materials. Each order carries the same formal brand
    requirements but different contact data, committee lists, and
    chamber-specific wording.
  </p>
  <p>
    I built an internal constrained template tool, not a document editor, that
    keeps seal placement, masthead type, grid, and margins locked while staff
    edit only the fields production allows. One <strong>LegislatorRecord</strong
    > feeds letterhead and envelope layouts with print-accurate preview and PDF export.
    Those PDFs support the variable-data workflows I use for personalized mailings,
    proofing, and production handoff.
  </p>

  <CaseStudySnapshot items={snapshotItems} />

  <h2>The Friction in Production</h2>
  <p>
    Before the system, repeat orders relied on separate files per legislator.
    Small differences in spacing and ink color compounded across all 170 members.
    When a legislator updated a phone number or committee assignment, staff had
    to hunt the right file and hope the layout still matched shop standards.
  </p>
  <p>The production workflow needed to solve three practical problems:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Brand compliance.</strong> Seal, masthead, and typography had to stay
      fixed regardless of who edited the order.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Data variation.</strong> Names, addresses, committee lists, and chamber
      wording all changed, but the structure could not.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Repeat accuracy.</strong> The same legislator might reorder letterhead
      multiple times a session; each run had to match the last without reintroducing
      spacing or color drift.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <figure class="case-figure">
    <Picture
      src={letterheadImg}
      alt="Letterhead editor with a form sidebar and print-accurate preview of NCGA stationery."
      formats={pictureFormats}
      widths={pictureWidths}
      sizes={pictureSizes}
    />
    <figcaption>
      Split-pane editor: governed fields on the left, locked template preview on
      the right. Sample data uses fictional legislator names.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>LOCKED vs DATA-DRIVEN</h2>
  <p>
    The core information architecture decision was explicit: everything the
    print shop is allowed to vary lives in a typed record; everything else is
    hardcoded into the template and never exposed in the form.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>LOCKED</strong> elements include the state seal, “North Carolina General
    Assembly” masthead, licensed typefaces, page grid, margins, and recycle mark geometry.
    <strong>DATA-DRIVEN</strong> fields include member name, chamber, office address,
    phone, committees, and ink color, with visibility toggles that hide sections on
    the letterhead without deleting the underlying data.
  </p>
  <p>
    A free-edit Word or InDesign template would have made the same drift easier
    to repeat. The constrained form works because it maps to what production
    actually allows.
  </p>

  <div class="template-flow" aria-label="Legislator record to output">
    <div class="template-flow__node">
      <span>Input</span>
      <strong>LegislatorRecord</strong>
    </div>
    <div class="template-flow__connector" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="template-flow__node template-flow__node--wide">
      <span>Locked template</span>
      <strong>Seal, masthead, grid, type</strong>
    </div>
    <div class="template-flow__connector" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="template-flow__node">
      <span>Output</span>
      <strong>Letterhead or envelope PDF</strong>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Same Record, Different Surfaces</h2>
  <p>
    Letterhead and envelopes share one data model but not one form. The
    letterhead editor exposes the full record plus visibility toggles for
    address, phone, and committees. The envelope editor uses a field subset: no
    phone or committees, and return addresses constrained to two NCGA buildings
    (Legislative Building or Legislative Office Building) with fixed ZIP codes
    rather than free text.
  </p>
  <p>
    Envelopes also omit the state seal, matching real production artwork, and
    explicitly defer recipient addresses to a downstream mail-merge pipeline.
    That boundary keeps the tool focused on return-address stationery staff
    produce in bulk, not one-off mailing lists.
  </p>

  <figure class="case-figure">
    <Picture
      src={envelopeImg}
      alt="Envelope editor with building picker and print-accurate envelope preview."
      formats={pictureFormats}
      widths={pictureWidths}
      sizes={pictureSizes}
    />
    <figcaption>
      Envelope surface: building picker instead of free-text address, no seal,
      recipients added later by mail merge.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Print Fidelity as UX</h2>
  <p>
    The on-screen preview is sized in real inches and points so staff can check
    what print will look like before exporting. Screen rendering uses DOM and
    Tailwind; PDF output uses a second renderer sharing the same business logic
    for chamber copy, ink colors, and visible committees. That split was
    deliberate: a screenshot export would not survive Acrobat; DOM alone cannot
    produce reliable print PDFs.
  </p>
  <p>
    Chamber selection drives both the masthead line and honorific automatically,
    so staff cannot accidentally pair “Senator” with House wording. Committee
    rows filter blank entries before preview and export, and long committee
    lists stress-test layout without breaking the locked grid.
  </p>

  <h2>Outcomes</h2>
  <p>
    With one governed template structure in place, personalized mailings to all
    170 members now go out in a single press pass instead of two, because the
    templates produce mail-merge-ready PDFs the production line accepts as is.
  </p>
  <p>
    Standardizing on one structure with governed variable data reduced mistakes
    on repeat stationery orders. Staff no longer maintain parallel files that
    drift in spacing and color; edits stay inside the template rules production
    already enforces.
  </p>
  <p>
    This case study covers the letterhead and envelope editor slice of broader
    NCGA work. Related NCGA work includes a press-split calculator for job
    planning, identity work, troubleshooting, job tickets, proofing, and
    high-volume production workflows, not shown here.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>

<style>
  .case-figure {
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
  }

  .case-figure :global(img) {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 0.375rem;
  }

  .case-figure figcaption {
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--muted-foreground);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .template-flow {
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
  }

  .template-flow__node {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 0.375rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: color-mix(in oklch, var(--background) 96%, var(--muted));
  }

  .template-flow__node span {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
    color: var(--muted-foreground);
    font-size: 0.6875rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.16em;
    line-height: 1.2;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .template-flow__node strong {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
  }

  .template-flow__connector {
    width: 1px;
    height: 1.25rem;
    margin-left: 1.25rem;
    background: var(--border);
  }

  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .template-flow {
      grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) 2rem minmax(0, 1.2fr) 2rem minmax(
          0,
          1fr
        );
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0;
    }

    .template-flow__connector {
      width: 100%;
      height: 1px;
      margin-left: 0;
    }
  }
</style>
